(12 points) We would like to estimate an unknown real number $1 \le x < \infty$. Suppose we have a Boolean function $f(\cdot)$ such that $f(y)$ returns true if $x \le y$, and $f(y)$ returns false otherwise. Describe an optimal algorithm that, given an error bound $0 < \epsilon < 1$, computes two nonnegative real numbers low and high satisfying
\begin{itemize}
    \item $low \le x \le high$
    \item $high - low \le \epsilon$
\end{itemize}
Argue that your algorithm invokes the function $f$ for at most $O(\lg \frac{1}{\epsilon} + \lg x)$ times.

